<li id="lithub_daily_widget-9" class="widget widget_lithub_daily_widget"><div class="lithub-daily-header"><a href="/category/lit-hub-daily/"><b>Lithub</b> Daily</a></div><h2 class="widgettitle">January 9, 2024</h2>
<a href="/lit-hub-daily-january-9-2024/"><img class="wp-image-192242 size-thumbnail aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/mary-childs-150x150.jpeg" alt="" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<ul>
 	<li>Mary Childs on <a href="https://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2024/01/08/ripping-ivy/" class="external" target="_blank">ripping ivy and writing nonfiction</a>.</li>
 	<li>The <a href="https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/books/story/2024-01-08/the-l-a-public-library-is-getting-into-book-publishing-why-it-makes-total-sense" class="external" target="_blank">Los Angeles Public Library is getting into publishing</a>.</li>
 	<li>"Even the biggest publishers are no match for <a href="https://www.thenation.com/article/economy/throwing-the-book-at-amazons-monopoly-hold-on-publishing/" class="external" target="_blank">Amazon’s death grip on the book market</a>."</li>
</ul>
<a title="LitHub Daily: May 1, 2015" href="/lit-hub-daily-january-9-2024/"><button>More News</button></a></li>
	    			</ul>
